Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

While Lebanon’s borders remain closed, the Lebanese Government is permitting a limited number of flights to operate on an exceptional basis to facilitate the repatriation of stranded travellers. The UK government is working closely with airlines, the Lebanese authorities and other governments to make sure options are available for you to return to the UK as soon as possible.
MEA flight to London on 13 April
There are a limited number of seats available on an exceptional Middle East Airlines (MEA) commercial flight (ME203) from Beirut to London on 13 April at 13:25 (local time) for British Nationals and their direct dependants wishing to return to the UK.
If you wish to travel on this flight, please contact MEA to book your ticket. This can be done via the telephone on +961 1 629 999 or on the internet at www.mea.com.lb. Please do not contact the British Embassy to reserve your flight.
Once you have booked your ticket, please send a scan or clear photograph of the photo page of your British passport, along with a copy of your booking confirmation, to the Embassy using the following email address beirut.consular@fco.gov.uk.Please book your flight and send the requested information to the Embassy by no later than 0900 on 13 April.
All travellers will need a valid travel document and the right to enter the United Kingdom.
In light of the road travel restrictions currently in place as part of measures to contain the COVID-19 outbreak, you should arrange your journey to the airport as soon as possible, and aim to arrive at least two hours in advance of the scheduled departure time.
Tickets will not be on sale at the airport. Do not travel to the airport without a confirmed ticket.
What to do
If you cannot leave Lebanon at this time, you should:
follow the advice of local authorities, including local measures to help minimise your risk of exposure to coronavirus
find accommodation that’s suitable for your needs
keep in regular contact with family and friends at home, so they know you are safe and well
follow the guidance in this travel advice on the restrictions in place in Lebanon, and what to do if you display symptoms of coronavirus
Future travel options
The UK government is working closely with airlines, the Lebanese authorities and other governments to secure further options for your return to the UK.
This travel advice will be updated when additional departure options become available.Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British Embassy on Twitter and Facebook.
Help and support
If you need urgent consular assistance, you can contact the Embassy on +961 (0)1 960800.
The Embassy cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available. To get the latest information, sign up for travel advice email alerts
Further information
See additional advice on making travel plans to return to the UK, or what to do if you cannot depart immediately.
